rish (of Norman origin): habitational name from La Varrenne in Seine-Maritime, France, named with a Gaulish element probably descriptive of alluvial land or sandy soil. This was the name of a major Norman family after the Conquest. In Ireland, this name has been Gaelicized as <b>Bharain</b>.","Irish: adopted as an English form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b> (see   Murnane  ,   Warner  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Warrens","meanings":["English: variant of   Warren   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Warrener","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>warrennier</i> ‘warrener’, an officer employed to watch over game in a park or game preserve. Compare   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Murnane","meanings":["Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b>, a shortened and dissimilated form of <b>Ó Manannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Manannán</i>’, name borne in Celtic mythology by a sea god associated with the Isle of Man. All three syllables appear in the variant <b>Marrinan</b>. This name has also been Anglicized as   Warren   and   Warner  ."]},{"name":"Waren","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Warne","meanings":["shortened form of   Warren  .","occasionally a habitational name from Wearne in Somerset. The place takes its name from a lost stream-name based on British <i>verno-</i> ‘alder, swamp’.","English:"]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"Ada","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin; it was not in general use before t